Chalco, Hang Seng, HSBC, Sun Hung Kai: Hong Kong Stocks Preview

-- B y   K a n a   N i s h i z a w a
-- 
2011-03-01T00:39:36Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-28/hang-seng-bank-hsbc-sun-hung-kai-hong-kong-stocks-preview.html
The following companies may have
significant price changes in Hong Kong trading today. Stock
symbols are in parentheses. Share prices are as of the last
close.  The  Hang Seng Index  climbed 1.4 percent to 23,338.02. The  Hang Seng  China Enterprises Index, which tracks so-called H
shares of Chinese companies, advanced 1.9 percent to 12,504.53.  Aluminum Corp. of China Ltd. (2600 HK): The listed unit of
China’s biggest maker of the lightweight metal reported a 2010
net income of 778 million yuan ($118 million), compared with a
loss of 4.6 billion yuan a year earlier. A Bloomberg survey of
13 analysts forecast earnings of 960.3 million yuan. Chalco, as
the producer is known, gained 3.2 percent to HK$7.69.    Hang Seng Bank Ltd . (11 HK): The Hong Kong-based lender
backed by  HSBC Holdings Plc  (5 HK) posted a 14 percent increase
in full-year profit as fee income advanced and costs related to
bad loans dropped. Net income rose to HK$14.9 billion ($1.9
billion) from HK$13.1 billion a year earlier, it said. The stock
declined 0.6 percent to HK$124.20.    HSBC Holdings Plc  (5 HK): Europe’s biggest bank by market
value said full-year net income rose to $13.2 billion in 2010
from $5.83 billion the previous year, missing the $13.72 billion
median estimate of 15 analysts surveyed by Bloomberg. The stock
gained 1.5 percent to HK$90.40.    Industrial & Commercial Bank of China  Ltd. (1398 HK): The
lender is targeting 880 billion yuan of new loans this year, the
Century Weekly magazine reported, citing unidentified bank
officials. The stock increased 1.9 percent to HK$5.98.  Mingyuan Medicare Development Co. (233 HK): The
biotechnology products maker said it will raise as much as
HK$259.2 million  through a placing of as many as 320 million
shares at 81 Hong Kong cents each. The stock was unchanged at 84
Hong Kong cents.    Sun Hung Kai Properties Ltd . (16 HK): The world’s largest
developer by market value said fiscal first-half underlying
profit rose 60 percent after it sold more apartments in Hong
Kong and rents increased. The stock gained 1.2 percent to
HK$125.80.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Kana Nishizawa in Hong Kong at 
 knishizawa5@bloomberg.net .  To contact the editor responsible for this story:
Nick Gentle at   ngentle2@bloomberg.net . 